p.text:
Unlike previous similar provisions (for example, Evidence Act 1898 
s 14CE
) the section does not require that the statement should have been made by a person who was actually engaged in the business. However, it may be expected that unless the person who made the statement was engaged in some relevant way with the conduct of the business, it will be more difficult to establish that the statement was made “in the course of, or for the purposes of,” the business. The section will certainly include statements made by a person who provides services to the business — irrespective of whether or not an employer/employee relationship exists: Ross McConnell Kitchen & Co Pty Ltd (in liq) v Ross (1985) 1 NSWLR 233. The section will include statements made by persons such as visiting doctors at hospitals, or perhaps bank officers in relation to the business of a particular customer — so long as the statements in question can be regarded as having been made for the purposes of the business whose records they allegedly form part: Re Marra Developments Ltd and the Companies Act [1979] 2 NSWLR 193 at 205; see also Trade Practices Commission v TNT Management Pty Ltd (1984) 56 ALR 647 at 659–660 .
